<P>THOUGH every lover of liberty is greatly obliged to you for your noble &amp; vigorous &s;tand again&s;t that more than Egypti|an bondage, wherewith we are threatened by the convention; yet I conceive you will give up a great advantage to which you are by law entitled, if you pro&s;ecute your de&s;ign of giving a particular an&s;wer to every part of the Appeal; becau&s;e in my opinion, only &s;ome parts of it ought to be an&s;wered, others to be pleaded to in bar, and the re&s;t of it is &s;ubject to a demurrer. For this purpo&s;e, I inclo&s;e you the form of a plea, an&s;wer, and demur|rer, which I beg you to in&s;ert in behalf of the public, and you will greatly oblige</P>
