<HEAD>A RULE of COURT.</HEAD>
<P>IT appearing to the court that the pleadings in this cau&s;e are to be publi&s;hed in a weekly news-paper, and that the aforegoing is of &s;ufficient length for one paper, it is ordered, on motion of Mr. Pleadwell, council for the appellant, that he have time to perfect and bring the &s;aid replication into court, until eight days next after publi&s;hing the aforegoing part thereof: And it is fur|ther ordered, that upon &s;ervice of a copy of this rule (by publi|cation thereof in the New-York Gazette, and weekly Mercu|ry) the &s;aid appellees, or their council, do not on any pretence what&s;oever, pre&s;ume to declare, either by &s;igns, words, or wri|ting, that the &s;aid plea and demurrer are unan&s;werable or that they of right ought to have judgement thereon again&s;t the appel|lant, until the &s;aid replication is perfected and filled, and the &s;ame be fully heard and con&s;idered by the council and judgment be pronounced thereupon in due form of law. And whereas it appears that the council of the &s;aid appellees hath, in contempt and derogation of the authority of this court, taken upon him|&s;elf
<PB N="176" REF="010857_0089_0F851F99AB36E590">to pronounce judgment on the &s;aid Appeal, it is ordered, that an attachment i&s;&s;ue again&s;t him to bring him before this court to an&s;wer for his &s;aid contempt.</P>
