<DIV2 TYPE="article">
<HEAD>A KICK FOR THE WHIPPER. [No. XIV.]</HEAD>
<BYLINE><HI>By Sir</HI> ISAAC FOOT.</BYLINE>
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><P>The temple of the <HI>Lord,</HI> the temple of the <HI>Lord,</HI> the temple of the <HI>Lord</HI> are the&s;e.</P>
<BIBL><HI>JEREMIAH.</HI></BIBL></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV3 TYPE="letter and catechism">
<DIV4 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD>To Sir ISAAC FOOT.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>THE following is de&s;ign'd as a <HI>Kick</HI> for a general fault of of the <HI>Whipper,</HI> in his erroneous and continual abu&s;e of of the word <HI>church;</HI> you &s;ee it is preceded by in&s;truction, which doubtle&s;s is the be&s;t way of correction. For this, I claim your promi&s;e made in your fir&s;t number, and am</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Sir, your humble Servant, <HI>A friend to truth.</HI></SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="catechism">
<P>A SHORT Catechi&s;m, for the in&s;truction of all in general, and of <HI>tories</HI> and <HI>high-churchmen</HI> in particular.</P>
<LIST>
<ITEM>1 Q. <HI>What doth the word</HI> church <HI>&s;ignify?</HI> A. Like the <HI>Greek</HI> word <HI>Ekkle&s;ia,</HI> it for the mo&s;t part &s;ignifies a number of profe&s;|&s;ed
<PB N="415" REF="010857_0208_0F851D918CE8A060">Chri&s;tians who meet together, in order publickly to wor&s;hip God, 1 <HI>Co.</HI> xiv. 23, 25. and el&s;ewhere. In a more &s;trict (but yet more comprehen&s;ive) &s;en&s;e, it means all <HI>real</HI> Chri&s;tians or members of the univer&s;al invi&s;ible church, <HI>Ephe&s;.</HI> v. 25, <HI>Colo&s;.</HI> i. 18. &amp;c. but the word <HI>Ekkle&s;ia</HI> tran&s;lated <HI>church,</HI> is &s;ometimes us'd with more latitude to expre&s;s a congregation of <HI>Jews, Acts</HI> vii. 38. and even to denominate a <HI>promi&s;cuous rab|ble (Acts</HI> xix. 32.) in the <HI>Theatre</HI> at <HI>Ephe&s;us</HI> which, for 2 long hours, cried, <HI>Great is Diana of the Epe&s;ians.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM>2 Q. <HI>Doth the word</HI> church <HI>al&s;o &s;ignify the</HI> hou&s;e <HI>in which people</HI> meet <HI>for divine wor&s;hip?</HI> A. Yes; 1 <HI>Cor.</HI> xiv. 35, and el&s;ewhere.</ITEM>
<ITEM>3. Q. <HI>What do you think of the word</HI> meeting? A. It is expre&s;|&s;ive of all that the word church is, (if the purpo&s;e of public wor&s;hip be implied) and &s;eem equivalent to the <HI>Greek</HI> word <HI>Sunagogee,</HI> us'd <HI>James</HI> ii. 2.</ITEM>
<ITEM>4. Q. <HI>Doth</HI> this <HI>word al&s;o &s;igni|fy the</HI> hou&s;e <HI>in which people a&s;&s;emble for the purpo&s;e afore&s;aid?</HI> A. Yes it oftentimes does; tho' it is common expre&s;sly to &s;ay <HI>meet|ing-hou&s;e;</HI> nor wou'd <HI>Church-hou&s;e</HI> be an improper expre&s;&s;ion, were it but authoriz'd by cu&s;tom.</ITEM>
<ITEM>5. Q. <HI>Are then the words</HI> church <HI>and</HI> meeting <HI>&s;ynonimous?</HI> A They are indeed, whether apply'd to the <HI>people</HI> form'd into congregations, or to the <HI>hou&s;e</HI> in which they a&s;&s;emble.</ITEM>
<ITEM>6. Q. <HI>But how can the word</HI> church <HI>or</HI> meeting <HI>be applied to</HI> hou&s;es? A. Hou&s;es &s;et apart for public wor&s;hip are figuratively call'd after the a&s;&s;embly of wor&s;hippers.</ITEM>
<ITEM>7. What think you of tho&s;e, <HI>who, meaning their own dear &s;elves, &s;ay, not</HI> our <HI>church, but</HI> the <HI>church,</HI> and <HI>generally expre&s;s the word</HI> CHURCH <HI>in</HI> capitals, <HI>as tho' they were afraid the un|wary reader wou'd mi&s;take, or think too meanly of</HI> them, <HI>and on the contrary, expre&s;s the word</HI> meeting <HI>diminutively as po&s;&s;ible?</HI> A. They virtually exclude all denominations of Chri&s;tians but them&s;elves out of the church univer&s;al, out of which according to &s;cripture there is no &s;alvation; and thus pattern after papi&s;ts, who affirm that the <HI>church of</HI> Rome alone is the <HI>Catholic</HI> or uni|ver&s;al church. But to put a more charitable con&s;truction on their way of expre&s;&s;ion, 'tis probable, <HI>they know not what they &s;ay, nor whereof they affirm,</HI> for they will hardly condemn what they call a &s;incere hone&s;t Pre&s;byterian.</ITEM>
<ITEM>8. Q. <HI>What think you of the words</HI> church <HI>and</HI> meeting <HI>as applied to</HI> hou&s;es <HI>&s;o call'd?</HI> A. That they may be promi&s;cuou&s;ly us'd, without regard to the denominations of Chri&s;tians therein a&s;&s;embling. Thus, e. g. We may properly eno'<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ay, <HI>Trinity</HI> meeting-hou&s;e, <HI>St. Paul's</HI> meeting-hou&s;e, <HI>Old and New Dutch</HI> meeting-hou&s;e, <HI>Old and New Pre&s;byterian</HI> meeting-hou&s;e, &amp;c. or on the con|trary we may call them all CHURCHES (e&s;pecially if we have rea&s;on to think there are at lea&s;t <HI>&s;ome real</HI> Chri&s;tians who a&s;&s;em|ble
<PB N="416" REF="010857_0209_0F851D92360C3E20">in them) without giving offence to any but the mo&s;t con|&s;ummate <HI>Bigots.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM>9. Q. <HI>What do &s;uch Bigots de&s;erve?</HI> A. To be <HI>kick'd</HI> out of the company of gentlemen and catholic Chri&s;ti|ans.</ITEM>
<ITEM>10. Q. <HI>Who appear to be of the number of &s;uch Bigots?</HI> A. <HI>Tabitha Kettle</HI> and her <HI>cook</HI>-mates.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P><HI>My humane catholic corre&s;pondent mu&s;t excu&s;e my informing the public that I have luckily di&s;cover'd him to be a re&s;pectable mem|ber of the</HI> Dutch church.</P>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD><HI>To Sir</HI> ISSAAC FOOT.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>AS you have not thought it worth <HI>your</HI> while to take any notice of the file of &s;oldiers, conducted by the <HI>magnani|mous</HI> Sergeant <HI>Plain Truth,</HI> de&s;tin'd, in conjunction with Capt, <HI>Tickle's</HI> irregulars, to antagonize the rear of the <HI>Whig's</HI> army, and as I have been &s;o curious as to take a <HI>review</HI> of them, I beg leave to &s;end you the re&s;ult.</P>
<P>Suppo&s;ing them <HI>truth-landers,</HI> they mu&s;t be a rabble of <HI>re|cruits</HI> from different provinces; for there are, it &s;eems, not only <HI>pa&s;t</HI> and pre&s;ent, (but would you believe it!) even <HI>future</HI> truths, about half the whole in number. They appear on the <HI>parade</HI> in ma&s;ks, but thro' the rents in their <HI>regimentals,</HI> tat|ter'd with long wearing, I di&s;cover'd the complexion of foreign <HI>mercenaries.</HI> In&s;tead of of <HI>cock-ades</HI> they were <HI>white ro&s;es.</HI> I need not tell you, they are well furni&s;h'd with <HI>&s;patterda&s;hes.</HI> Tho' perfect <HI>dwarfs,</HI> they &s;trut and blu&s;ter mo&s;t <HI>gigantically,</HI> and tho' very puerile in appearance, are mighty pert, &s;ancy, brazen|fac'd fellows; but as great <HI>braggadochios</HI> as they are, they are hor|ribly afraid of a Watch Tower, &amp;c. They have a <HI>kettle drum,</HI> which being empty makes a great tinkling, and their <HI>&s;tandard</HI> &s;eems to be a rag of the &s;carlet W&mdash;. In lieu of <HI>mu&s;quets</HI> they carry <HI>blunder-bu&s;&s;es,</HI> and in&s;tead of <HI>&s;words</HI> they wear <HI>dung|forks.</HI> Their <HI>balls</HI> indeed are <HI>lead;</HI> but their <HI>powder</HI> tho' it &s;mells &s;trong of <HI>brim&s;tone,</HI> contains little or no <HI>&s;alt of Peter;</HI> &s;o that their cartridges do little more than <HI>burn, hi&s;s and bounce, wa&s;te paper, &s;tink and die.</HI></P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>I am, Sir, your humble Servant, ARGUS.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV3>
